{"title_page": "Kevin Davies", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Kevin Davies\n| image               = Kevin Davies August 2011.jpg\n| image_size          = 200\n| caption             = Davies training with [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in 2011\n| fullname            = Kevin Cyril Davies<ref name=Hugman1011>{{cite book |editor-first=Barry J. |editor-last=Hugman |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311 |year=2010 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |page=108}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1977|3|26|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman1011/>\n| birth_place         = [[Sheffield]], England\n| height              = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}<ref name=Hugman1011/>\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub         = \n| youthyears1         = |youthclubs1 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| youthyears2         = {{0|0000}}\u20131993 | youthclubs2 = [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]\n| years1              = 1993\u20131997 |clubs1 = [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]           |caps1 = 129 |goals1 = 22\n| years2              = 1997\u20131998 |clubs2 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]             |caps2 = 25  |goals2 = 9\n| years3              = 1998\u20131999 |clubs3 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]   |caps3 = 23  |goals3 = 1\n| years4              = 1999\u20132003 |clubs4 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]             |caps4 = 82  |goals4 = 10\n| years5              = 2002      |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] (loan)          |caps5 = 9   |goals5 = 3\n| years6              = 2003\u20132013 |clubs6 = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]   |caps6 = 351 |goals6 = 74\n| years7              = 2013\u20132015 |clubs7 = [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] |caps7 = 70  |goals7 = 4\n| totalcaps = 689 |totalgoals = 123\n| nationalyears1      = 1994\u20131995 |nationalteam1 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] |nationalcaps1 = 8 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2      = 1997\u20132000 |nationalteam2 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] |nationalcaps2 = 3 |nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3      = 2010      |nationalteam3 = [[England national football team|England]]              |nationalcaps3 = 1 |nationalgoals3 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs1 = [[Southport F.C.|Southport]]\n}}\n'''Kevin Cyril Davies''' (born 26 March 1977) is an English former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] for [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]], [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]. He managed [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] in the  2017\u201318 season, before his contract was terminated on 30 April 2018.\n\nDavies originally made his name as a vital part of the Chesterfield team which reached the semi-finals of the [[FA Cup]] in 1997. He left Chesterfield at the end of that season, having made 148 appearances for the club and joined [[Premier League]] club Southampton in May 1997. He only spent one season at Southampton, making 30 appearances, before he joined Premier League club Blackburn Rovers in a club-record \u00a37.5&nbsp;million deal. Once again, he spent a single season at the club, making 29 appearances, before rejoining Southampton in 1999. In his second spell at the club, he made 95 appearances, also spending part of 2002 on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] to [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club Millwall, where he made nine appearances. Released by Southampton at the end of the [[2002\u201303 Southampton F.C. season|2002\u201303 season]], he joined Premier League club Bolton Wanderers on a free transfer. He was made Bolton [[captain (association football)|team captain]] in January 2009, but began to fall out of favour at Bolton towards the end of the [[2012\u201313 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]], and the club decided against renewing his contract. Davies made 407 appearances for Bolton, scoring 85 goals, then played two seasons at Preston North End before retiring.\n\nHe made three appearances for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 team]] between 1997 and 2000. At the age of 33, Davies made his international debut, and only appearance, for [[England national football team|England]] against [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]] in a 0\u20130 draw on 12 October 2010, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Chesterfield===\nBorn in [[Sheffield]], South Yorkshire,<ref name=Hugman1011/> Davies played as a schoolboy with his boyhood club [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], but was released at the age of 15.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} He was taken on trial at [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]<ref name=\"bbc 01-10\">{{cite news|last=Magowan |first=Alistair |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/8470180.stm |title=Football \u2013 An old-fashioned centre-forward |publisher=BBC Sport |date= 21 January 2010|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> and served his traineeship with the club.<ref name=Hugman1011/> Davies broke into the club's first team after several months.<ref name=\"bbc 01-10\"/> He became Chesterfield's second youngest ever first-team player when he appeared against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie, aged only 16, on 22 September 1993.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Tomlinson |title=Kevin Davies announces retirement from football |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9978529/kevin-davies-announces-retirement-from-football |publisher=Sky Sports |date=4 September 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=Rothmans1993-94/> He signed his first professional contract with the club in April 1994.<ref name=Hugman1011/>\n\nGenerally, Davies' goalscoring form at Chesterfield was unspectacular, playing mostly wide in midfield and scoring his best total of 11 goals in the [[1994-95 in English football|1994\u201395]] promotion season from the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] via the play-offs.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} In his final season at [[Saltergate]] he managed a mere three goals from 34 [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] matches but made a major contribution to the Spireites' best-ever [[FA Cup]] run, including a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] at [[Burnden Park]] in a fourth round tie against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and an earlier strike against [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] in the 2nd round.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/season-of-dreaming-spireites-1266972.html\n|title=Season of dreaming Spireites\n|newspaper=The Independent\n|date=13 April 1997|accessdate=28 September 2012\n|location=London\n|first=Jamie\n|last=Hewitt}}</ref> Despite his relative lack of goals, his skilful play was still attracting attention from [[Premier League]] and [[Football League First Division|First Division]] clubs during his contribution to Chesterfield's FA Cup exploits, which culminated in a semi-final replay defeat against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/middlesbrough-v-chesterfield-22-april-1997-25605/ |title=Middlesbrough v Chesterfield, 22 April 1997 |work=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs a youngster, Davies was far from the aggressive centre-forward he subsequently became at Bolton.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} At Chesterfield, although very well-built and strong for a teenager, he was known for his skill and intelligence, and it was these qualities that attracted the attention of Southampton manager [[Graeme Souness]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1319536/Kevin-Davies--ageing-Reggae-Boy-verge-England-debut-33.html | location=London | newspaper=Daily Mail | first=Dan | last=Ripley | title=Kevin Davies \u2013 an ageing Reggae Boy finally on the verge of an England debut at 33 | date=11 October 2010}}{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Southampton===\nDavies moved to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in May 1997 and, in his first spell with them, scored nine league goals, one of which was a notable solo goal in a 2\u20130 win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/20319.stm |title=Goodison gloom as Saints take points |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 November 1997 |accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> He also scored the lone goals in historic 1\u20130 wins against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/dell-hell-for-offcolour-red-devils-26199106.html |title=Dell hell for off-colour Red Devils |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=20 January 1998 |accessdate=29 March 2018}}</ref> and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]],<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-davies-strike-is-decisive-as-saints-defy-chelsea-1291159.html\n|title=Davies' strike is decisive as Saints defy Chelsea\n|newspaper=The Independent |location=London\n|date=30 December 1997 |accessdate=1 October 2012\n |first=Glenn\n |last=Moore}}</ref> and the equaliser in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-liverpool-bow-to-saint-davies-1240318.html\n|title=Liverpool bow to Saint Davies\n|newspaper=The Independent |location=London\n|date=21 September 1997 |accessdate=1 October 2012\n |first=Nick\n |last=Harris}}</ref>\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\n[[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] signed him for \u00a37.5&nbsp;million in July 1998, ten times what Southampton had paid for him a year earlier and also a club record.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} Chesterfield received no more money from the switch, having failed to negotiate a sell-on clause.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} As part of the deal, [[James Beattie (footballer)|James Beattie]] went the other way.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} However, Davies scored just one league goal, the winner in a victory over [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], in 21 appearances for the club.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-davies-scores--and-no-kidding-1189513.html |title=Davies scores \u2013 and no kidding |newspaper=The Independent |date=5 December 1998 |accessdate=15 February 2010 | location=London | first=Dave | last=Hadfield}}</ref> He scored a further goal in the FA Cup, also against Charlton Athletic, and played a [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] match that season.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-fa-cup-ilic-error-covers-up-charlton-deficiency-1045017.html|title=FA Cup: Ilic error covers up Charlton deficiency |newspaper=The Independent |date=3 January 1999 |accessdate=15 February 2010 | location=London | first=Dave | last=Hadfield}}</ref> At the end of the campaign, Blackburn were relegated a year after finishing sixth in the league and a mere four years after [[1994\u201395 FA Premier League|winning the league]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Return to Southampton===\nSouthampton re-signed their former striker in exchange for [[Egil \u00d8stenstad]] in August 1999.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} However, just two league matches into his return at Southampton, Davies found himself sent off in a defeat against Liverpool after coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Mark Hughes]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} He struggled to gain a first-team place throughout the next four years, and was more often than not a substitute.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} For the [[2002\u201303 Millwall F.C. season|2002\u201303 season]] Davies went on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] to [[Millwall F.C.|Milwall]] in the First Division, where he played nine times, scoring three goals.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Bolton Wanderers===\n[[File:Kevin Davies.png|thumb|upright|Davies lining up for [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in 2008]]\n\nIn summer 2003, he joined Bolton having been released by Southampton.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} In a season where he rediscovered his best form, he scored ten times and started every league match.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} He ended the season by winning the club's Player of the Year award and scored a consolation goal for his team in the [[2004 Football League Cup Final|2004 League Cup Final]] against Middlesbrough at the [[Millennium Stadium]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nDavies is frequently cited as being the player in the Premier League that commits the most fouls, committing more offences than any other Premier League player in for three consecutive seasons from 2004 to 2007.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} In the 2003\u201304 and 2007\u201308 seasons, Davies was slightly better behaved, committing the second highest number of fouls per season.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} In his Bolton career Davies has committed over 1,000 fouls, more than any other Premier League player in the competition's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/Statistics/0,,12306,00.html |title=2007/2008 |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=22 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101230130252/http://www.premierleague.com/page/Statistics/0%2C%2C12306%2C00.html |archivedate=30 December 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20051224/ai_n15962443 FOOTBALL: TODAY'S TOP 20: HIGHEST FOULS PER GAME RATIO SO FAR THIS | Independent, The (London) | Find Articles at BNET.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213144707/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20051224/ai_n15962443 |date=13 February 2009 }}</ref> At the same time Davies has also featured near the top of the list of most fouled players.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-sport/article-23617294-details/Bolton+don't+play+proper+football,+says+Van+Persie/article.do |title=Bolton don't play proper football, says Van Persie |newspaper=Evening Standard |location=London |accessdate=22 January 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDuring a post-match interview with the BBC after a match against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in January 2009, during which he had been accused of deliberately trying to injure [[Ga\u00ebl Clichy]] in a challenge, he replied that some Arsenal players tried to \"con the referee\". He added ''\"A few of them let out a big scream, which is a bit embarrassing because it is a man's game&nbsp;... in my eyes that is cheating the referee&nbsp;... you just have to get on with the game.\"''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bolton_wanderers/7823592.stm |title=Davies angered by Arsenal conduct |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> On 10 September 2011. he received his 100th yellow card in the Premier League for a foul on Manchester United's [[Patrice Evra]] and when he received another booking against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] on 11 February 2012, he became the joint holder of the record for most yellow cards in Premier League history, alongside [[Lee Bowyer]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} [[Paul Scholes]] has equaled his Premier League yellow card record and [[Gareth Barry]] has surpassed this record.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nOn 8 November 2007, Davies scored a goal away to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] at the [[Allianz Arena]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} Davies's late effort earned Bolton a crucial away point from the 2\u20132 draw in the UEFA Cup group stage.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nOn 12 April 2008, Davies scored his 100th career goal in a 1\u20130 win over West Ham at the [[Reebok Stadium]], despite dislocating a finger during the match and having it placed back into its socket allowing him to play on.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.co.uk/sport/football/tm_headline=kev-s-only-gone-and-ton-it&method=full&objectid=20381874&siteid=93463-name_page.html |title=Kev's only gone and ton it! |newspaper=The Sunday People |location=London |date=13 April 2008 |accessdate=22 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204004603/http://www.people.co.uk/sport/football/tm_headline%3Dkev-s-only-gone-and-ton-it%26method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D20381874%26siteid%3D93463-name_page.html |archivedate=4 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday 3 May 2008, he made his return from a broken hand to help Bolton retain their Premier League status.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nOver the summer of 2008, [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] tried to sign Kevin Davies from Bolton, but the club turned down their offer.<ref>[http://mannyroad.com/bolton-news-kevin-davies-hull/01/08/2008/ Bolton News ignore Kevin Davies to Hull story] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714031339/http://mannyroad.com/bolton-news-kevin-davies-hull/01/08/2008/ |date=14 July 2011 }}. Manny Road. 1 August 2008.</ref> Davies then signed a new contract with Bolton would keep him at the club until 2011.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/2008/08/29/bolton-s-kevin-davies-signs-lucrative-new-contract-115875-20716061/ Bolton's Kevin Davies signs lucrative new contract]. ''Daily Mirror''. London. 29 August 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2009, Davies became captain of Bolton following the sale of [[Kevin Nolan]] to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\"bbc 01-10\"/> The same day, Davies' first match as captain saw him score two goals in Bolton's 3\u20132 victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] as well as equalling his record for goals in a Premier League season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lyon |first=Sam |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7856381.stm |title=Bolton 3\u20132 Tottenham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 January 2009 |accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> In the following match, at home against West Ham, he scored his 50th goal for Bolton, and his 10th of the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shea |first=Julian |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7885825.stm |title=Bolton 2\u20131 West Ham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2009 |accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009, Davies stated that he would like to stay at Bolton for the rest of his career.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/clubs/premier-league/bolton-wanderers/Kevin-Davies-promises-to-finish-his-career-at-Bolton-article106743.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805004813/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/clubs/premier-league/bolton-wanderers/Kevin-Davies-promises-to-finish-his-career-at-Bolton-article106743.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Kevin Davies promises to finish his career at Bolton |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=22 January 2010 }}</ref> On 13 March 2010, Davies scored the first penalty of his career, netting the second from the spot in a 4\u20130 home win over Wigan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8559619.stm |title=Bolton 4\u20130 Wigan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2010 |accessdate=13 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nDavies set a Premier League records for the most fouls in a season in 2009\u201310, committing 120 such offences.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} In the 2010\u201311 season he went on to break his own record with 121 fouls.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1389201/PREMIER-LEAGUE-LIVE-Follow-relegation-drama-Survival-Sunday.html | location=London | newspaper=Daily Mail | first=Dan | last=Ripley | title=Premier League live: Blackpool and Birmingham relegated after defeats at Manchester United and Tottenham respectively \u2013 as it happened | date=22 May 2011}}{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\nDavies was relegated with Bolton at the end of the 2011\u201312 season, but shortly after, he signed a new one-year deal with the club and assured the fans he would stay to get Bolton back to the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bwfc.co.uk/page/General/0,,1004~2776253,00.html |title=Davies signs new one-year deal |date=18 May 2012 |publisher=Bolton Wanderers F.C |accessdate=18 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520063442/http://www.bwfc.co.uk/page/General/0%2C%2C1004~2776253%2C00.html |archivedate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> He made his 400th appearance for the club at [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on 2 February 2013.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nOn 26 March 2013, Bolton announced that they would not be offering Davies a new contract, which would make that season his final for the club.<ref name=BBC270313>{{cite web|title=Kevin Davies: Bolton captain to leave Wanderers after 10 seasons |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21942886|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 July 2013|date=27 March 2013}}</ref> Following this announcement, Davies played no further matches that season, being initially dropped to the bench before eventually being left out of match day squads completely, with reserve-team strikers being preferred instead.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Preston North End===\nOn 10 July 2013, Davies signed a two-year contract with [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnefc.net/news/article/kevin-davies-signs100713-905299.aspx |title=Kevin Davies signs! |publisher=Preston North End F.C. |date=10 July 2013 |accessdate=10 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130714083716/http://www.pnefc.net/news/article/kevin-davies-signs100713-905299.aspx |archivedate=14 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin Davies: Preston North End sign ex-Bolton & England striker|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23254820|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 July 2013|date=10 July 2013}}</ref> He made his league debut for Preston on 3 August in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]], and drew praise from his manager for his performance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11697/8853684/grayson-expects-davies-impact |title=Grayson expects Davies impact |publisher=Sky Sports |date=3 August 2013 |accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref> His first goal for Preston was a penalty in a 2\u20131 win over [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] on 9 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23925593 |title=Preston 2\u20131 Oldham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 September 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> He went on to score the only goal in a 1\u20130 win over [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in the FA Cup on 9 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25163413 |title=Wycombe 0\u20131 Preston |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 December 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2015, he scored his 150th career goal and his first of the season, heading in [[Paul Gallagher (footballer)|Paul Gallagher]]'s cross to win a home match against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Preston 1\u20130 Coventry|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31070837|accessdate=26 May 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 February 2015}}</ref> He played 22 minutes as a substitute for hat-trick scorer [[Jermaine Beckford]] on 24 May as Preston won 4\u20130 in the [[2015 Football League One play-off Final|play-off final]] against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name=\"Preston North End 4\u20130 Swindon Town\">{{cite news|last=Middleton|first=Nathan|title=Preston North End 4\u20130 Swindon Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32770740|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 May 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2015, Davies announced his retirement from football after 22 years in the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin Davies: Ex-Preston, Bolton and England striker retires|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34151258|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 September 2015|date=4 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDavies was asked near the end of the 2009\u201310 season if he was eligible to play for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} Davies is, to his own knowledge, ineligible to represent Scotland, but further explained he would reject any call-up to the Scottish or Welsh teams even if it was possible.<ref>{{cite news|last=Iles|first=Marc|title=Davies rejects Scotland offer|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/8305907.Davies_rejects_Scotland_offer/|newspaper=The Bolton News|accessdate=13 October 2010|date=2 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 33, Davies was called up to the England squad for the first time in his career for the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group G|UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] match against [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]] on 12 October 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9056797.stm|title=England boss Fabio Capello calls up Kevin Davies |date= 4 October 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref> He made his debut as a 69th-minute substitute for [[Peter Crouch]] and received a [[Yellow card (sport)|yellow card]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNulty |first=Phil |title=England 0 Montenegro 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9086010.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 October 2010|date=12 October 2010}}</ref> At 33 years and 200 days, he became the oldest England debutant since the 38-year-old [[Leslie Compton]] in 1950.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n==Style of play==\nDavies was known for his bustling, physical playing style; he has committed more [[foul (football)|fouls]] than any other player in the history of the Premier League, although conversely he is also one of the most fouled.<ref name=\"bbc 01-10\"/>\n\n==Managerial career==\nDavies was appointed manager of [[National League North]] club [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] on 18 October 2017 on a two-and-a-half-year contract.<ref name=SouthportIn>{{cite news |first=Jamie |last=Lopez |title=Former Bolton and England striker Kevin Davies named new Southport FC manager |url=http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/sport/football/news/former-bolton-england-striker-kevin-13779575 |newspaper=Southport Visiter |date=18 October 2017 |accessdate=18 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2018 [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] announced that Davies had been released from his managerial duties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southport Football Club And Kevin Davies Part Company|url=https://southportfc.net/statement-southport-football-club-and-kevin-davies-part-company/|publisher=Southport F.C.|accessdate=30 April 2018|date=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the half brother of fellow footballer [[Jamie Jackson (footballer)|Jamie Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chesterfield-fc.co.uk/page/ClubAnnouncements/0,,10435~814524,00.html |title=Two Jamies get their chance |publisher=Chesterfield F.C. |accessdate=18 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004124558/http://www.chesterfield-fc.co.uk/page/ClubAnnouncements/0%2C%2C10435~814524%2C00.html |archivedate= 4 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.derbyshiretimes.co.uk/sport/Blues-add-teen-spirit.1442245.jp |title=Blues add teen spirit |newspaper=Derbyshire Times |location=Chesterfield |date=13 April 2006 |accessdate=18 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]]\n|[[1993\u201394 Chesterfield F.C. season|1993\u201394]]<ref name=Rothmans1993-94>{{cite book |editor-first=Jack |editor-last=Rollin |title=Rothmans Football Yearbook 1994\u201395 |year=1994 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7472-7857-3 |pages=166\u2013167, 616\u2013622, 637\u2013638, 655}}</ref>\n|[[Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n|24||4||0||0||2||0||2{{efn|name=FLT|Appearances in [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]]}}||0||28||4\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Chesterfield F.C. season|1994\u201395]]<ref name=Rothmans1994-95>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Rothmans Football Yearbook 1995\u201396 |year=1995 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7472-7823-8 |pages=124\u2013125, 552\u2013553, 578\u2013584, 608\u2013611, 597\u2013599}}</ref>\n|Third Division\n|41||11||1||0||3||1||4{{efn|Two appearances and one goal in Football League Trophy, two appearances in [[EFL League Two play-offs|Third Division play-offs]]}}||1||49||13\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Chesterfield F.C. season|1995\u201396]]<ref name=Rothmans1995-96>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Rothmans Football Yearbook 1996\u201397 |year=1996 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7472-7781-1 |pages=