nks==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Bolton Wanderers F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Southport F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chesterfield F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Southport F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) managers]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Davies"}
{"title_page": "Hida, S\u0103laj", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = S\u0103laj\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in S\u0103laj County\n|name                  = Hida\n|image_map             = Hida jud Salaj.png\n|image_skyline         = Biserica din Baica.jpg\n|image_caption         = Wooden Church in Baica\n|leader_name           = Dumitru Petru\u0219<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party          = PNL\n|area_total_km2        = 101.72\n|coordinates           = {{coord|47|03|43|N|23|18|32|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n|website= [http://www.comunahida.ro www.comunahida.ro]\n}}\n'''Hida''' ({{lang-hu|Hidalm\u00e1s}}; {{lang-yi|\u05d4\u05d9\u05d3\u05d0\u05dc\u05de\u05d0\u05e9|translit=Hidalmash}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[S\u0103laj County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of eight villages: Baica (''B\u00e1nyika''), Hida, Miluani (''Milv\u00e1ny''), P\u0103duri\u0219 (''Tyikl\u00f3''), Rac\u00e2\u0219 (''Alm\u00e1sr\u00e1kos''), S\u00e2npetru Alma\u0219ului (''F\u00fczesszentp\u00e9ter''), Stupini (''F\u00fczes'') and Trestia (''Koml\u00f3s\u00fajfalu'').\n\n==Miluani==\nThe village of Miluani had 112 inhabitants in 2002 and is famous for its grain and sunflower production.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\nThe settlement was first mentioned in Hungarian documents in 1320 as ''Miluad''. From the 13th century the area was property of the Hungarian Zsombor clan. In the 14th century it was donated to the [[Elef\u00e1nthy family]]. A [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]] church was built in the 16th century and a new one in 1920. Miluani is the filia of the [[Roman Catholic]] parish of Chidea; traditionally its vicars were [[Franciscans]] until 1897. Local [[Unitarianism|Unitarians]] also belongs to Chidea. Miluani was also a center of the [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic|Greek-Catholic]] arch-deaconry. [http://mek.oszk.hu/04700/04750/html/57.html]\n\nMiluani historically was part of [[Transylvania]] within the [[Kingdom of Hungary]]. It belonged to [[Doboka County]] until 1876, when it was incorporated into [[Kolozs]] county. In 1920, after [[World War I]] and the [[Treaty of Trianon]], the village, as part of Transylvania, was handed over to [[Romania]].\n\nIn 1940, by the [[Second Vienna Arbitration]], it was again annexed by Hungary. In 1944 ethnic Romanian rebels of Miluani burnt up the Hungarian Reformed Church's archive in Hida. [http://udvardy.adatbank.transindex.ro/?action=intezmeny&intezmeny=3062&intezmeny_sz=Reform%C3%A1tus%20Egyh%C3%A1z&kezd=211]\nThe Jewish population of Hidalm\u00e1s (26.0% in 1910) was deported to Auschwitz by the Hungarian government in May 1944.\n \nAmong those who have resided in the village include [[S\u00e1ndor Kendi]], a Hungarian magnate and [[J\u00f3zsef Ny\u00edr\u0151]], a Hungarian writer and politician, and vicar in Miluani.\n[[File:Biserica din Hida.jpg|260px|thumb|right|Wooden Church in Hida, built in the 18th century, historic monument]]\n\n== Sights ==\n* Wooden Church in Baica, built in the 17th century (1645), historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Baica_Biserica_lemn_r.htm welcometoromania.ro - Wooden Church in Baica, S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Wooden Church in Hida, built in the 18th century (1717), historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Hida_Biserica_lemn_r.htm welcometoromania.ro - Wooden Church in Hida,. S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Wooden Church in Rac\u00e2\u0219, built in the 16th century (1558), historic monument\n* Wooden Church in S\u00e2npetru Alma\u0219ului, built in the 18th century (1795), historic monument\n* Orthodox Church in Miluani, built in the 16th century, historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Miluani_Biserica_Ortodoxa_r.htm welcometoromania.ro - Orthodox Church in Miluani, S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Hida, Manor Hatfaludy, built in the 20th century (1916), historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Hida_Conacul_Hatfaludy_e.htm welcometoromania.ro - Manor Hatfaludy, Hida, S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref> \n* Hida, Devil's Rock Nature reserve (Natural monument)<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Hida_Stanca_Dracului_e.htm welcometoromania.ro - Hida, Devil's Rock Natural reserve], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Meadow with daffodils from Rac\u00e2\u0219-Hida, Natural reserve\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mek.oszk.hu/04700/04750/html/57.html Petri M\u00f3r: Szil\u00e1gy v\u00e1rmegye monographi\u00e1ja]\n* [http://www.cimec.ro/Monumente/LacaseCult/FR/Documente/ASP/detaliu.asp?k=23610-1 CIMEC \u2013 \u00c9tablissements religieux en Roumanie]\n* [http://www.cimec.ro/Monumente/LacaseCult/FR/Documente/ASP/detaliu.asp?k=31281-1 CIMEC \u2013 \u00c9tablissements religieux en Roumanie]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722205719/http://arheologie.ulbsibiu.ro/publicatii/bibliotheca/relatii%20interetnice%20in%20transilvania/7%20salagean/articol1.htm Etnikumk\u00f6zi kapcsolatok Erd\u00e9lyben]\n* [http://www.kereso.hu/cimszo/milv%E1ny Keres\u0151: Milv\u00e1ny]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.1000ev.hu/index.php?a=3&param=5765 1877. \u00e9vi I. t\u00f6rv\u00e9nycikk]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{S\u0103laj County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hida}}\n[[Category:Communes in S\u0103laj County]]\n\n[[eo:Miluani]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = S\u0103laj\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in S\u0103laj County\n|name                  = Hida\n|image_map             = Hida jud Salaj.png\n|image_skyline         = Biserica din Baica.jpg\n|image_caption         = Wooden Church in Baica\n|leader_name           = Dumitru Petri\u0219\n|leader_party          = [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|PDL]] \n|area_total_km2        = 101.72\n|coordinates           = {{coord|47|03|43|N|23|18|32|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n|website= [http://www.comunahida.ro www.comunahida.ro]\n}}\n'''Hida''' ({{lang-hu|Hidalm\u00e1s}}; {{lang-yi|\u05d4\u05d9\u05d3\u05d0\u05dc\u05de\u05d0\u05e9|translit=Hidalmash}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[S\u0103laj County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of eight villages: Baica (''B\u00e1nyika''), Hida, Miluani (''Milv\u00e1ny''), P\u0103duri\u0219 (''Tyikl\u00f3''), Rac\u00e2\u0219 (''Alm\u00e1sr\u00e1kos''), S\u00e2npetru Alma\u0219ului (''F\u00fczesszentp\u00e9ter''), Stupini (''F\u00fczes'') and Trestia (''Koml\u00f3s\u00fajfalu'').\n\n==Miluani==\nThe village of Miluani had 112 inhabitants in 2002 and is famous for its grain and sunflower production.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\nThe settlement was first mentioned in Hungarian documents in 1320 as ''Miluad''. From the 13th century the area was property of the Hungarian Zsombor clan. In the 14th century it was donated to the [[Elef\u00e1nthy family]]. A [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]] church was built in the 16th century and a new one in 1920. Miluani is the filia of the [[Roman Catholic]] parish of Chidea; traditionally its vicars were [[Franciscans]] until 1897. Local [[Unitarianism|Unitarians]] also belongs to Chidea. Miluani was also a center of the [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic|Greek-Catholic]] arch-deaconry. [http://mek.oszk.hu/04700/04750/html/57.html]\n\nMiluani historically was part of [[Transylvania]] within the [[Kingdom of Hungary]]. It belonged to [[Doboka County]] until 1876, when it was incorporated into [[Kolozs]] county. In 1920, after [[World War I]] and the [[Treaty of Trianon]], the village, as part of Transylvania, was handed over to [[Romania]].\n\nIn 1940, by the [[Second Vienna Arbitration]], it was again annexed by Hungary. In 1944 ethnic Romanian rebels of Miluani burnt up the Hungarian Reformed Church's archive in Hida. [http://udvardy.adatbank.transindex.ro/?action=intezmeny&intezmeny=3062&intezmeny_sz=Reform%C3%A1tus%20Egyh%C3%A1z&kezd=211]\nThe Jewish population of Hidalm\u00e1s (26.0% in 1910) was deported to Auschwitz by the Hungarian government in May 1944.\n \nAmong those who have resided in the village include [[S\u00e1ndor Kendi]], a Hungarian magnate and [[J\u00f3zsef Ny\u00edr\u0151]], a Hungarian writer and politician, and vicar in Miluani.\n[[File:Biserica din Hida.jpg|260px|thumb|right|Wooden Church in Hida, built in the 18th century, historic monument]]\n\n== Sights ==\n* Wooden Church in Baica, built in the 17th century (1645), historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Baica_Biserica_lemn_r.htm welcometoromania.ro - Wooden Church in Baica, S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Wooden Church in Hida, built in the 18th century (1717), historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Hida_Biserica_lemn_r.htm welcometoromania.ro - Wooden Church in Hida,. S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Wooden Church in Rac\u00e2\u0219, built in the 16th century (1558), historic monument\n* Wooden Church in S\u00e2npetru Alma\u0219ului, built in the 18th century (1795), historic monument\n* Orthodox Church in Miluani, built in the 16th century, historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Miluani_Biserica_Ortodoxa_r.htm welcometoromania.ro - Orthodox Church in Miluani, S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Hida, Manor Hatfaludy, built in the 20th century (1916), historic monument<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Hida_Conacul_Hatfaludy_e.htm welcometoromania.ro - Manor Hatfaludy, Hida, S\u0103laj County], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref> \n* Hida, Devil's Rock Nature reserve (Natural monument)<ref>[http://www.welcometoromania.ro/DN1g/DN1g_Hida_Stanca_Dracului_e.htm welcometoromania.ro - Hida, Devil's Rock Natural reserve], retrieved on May 16, 2012</ref>\n* Meadow with daffodils from Rac\u00e2\u0219-Hida, Natural reserve\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mek.oszk.hu/04700/04750/html/57.html Petri M\u00f3r: Szil\u00e1gy v\u00e1rmegye monographi\u00e1ja]\n* [http://www.cimec.ro/Monumente/LacaseCult/FR/Documente/ASP/detaliu.asp?k=23610-1 CIMEC \u2013 \u00c9tablissements religieux en Roumanie]\n* [http://www.cimec.ro/Monumente/LacaseCult/FR/Documente/ASP/detaliu.asp?k=31281-1 CIMEC \u2013 \u00c9tablissements religieux en Roumanie]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722205719/http://arheologie.ulbsibiu.ro/publicatii/bibliotheca/relatii%20interetnice%20in%20transilvania/7%20salagean/articol1.htm Etnikumk\u00f6zi kapcsolatok Erd\u00e9lyben]\n* [http://www.kereso.hu/cimszo/milv%E1ny Keres\u0151: Milv\u00e1ny]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.1000ev.hu/index.php?a=3&param=5765 1877. \u00e9vi I. t\u00f6rv\u00e9nycikk]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{S\u0103laj County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hida}}\n[[Category:Communes in S\u0103laj County]]\n\n[[eo:Miluani]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hida,_S%C4%83laj"}
{"title_page": "Thor Bj\u00f8rklund", "text_new": "[[image:Osthyvel 20050723 001.jpg|thumb|250 px|''Osteh\u00f8vel'']]\n'''Thor Bj\u00f8rklund''' (October 30, 1889 \u2013 December 8, 1975) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[inventor]] and businessman. He is best known as the [[inventor]] of ''Osteh\u00f8vel'', a popular [[cheese slicer]] which developed into an important Norwegian export product.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://nbl.snl.no/Thor_Bj%C3%B8rklund|title = Thor Bj\u00f8rklund |publisher = Norsk biografisk leksikon|accessdate= December 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bjorklund-1925.no/index.php/en/about-us/51-history ''About Us: History'' (Thor Bj\u00f8rklund & S\u00f8nner AS)]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://snl.no/osteh%C3%B8vel|title = Osteh\u00f8vel |publisher =Store norske leksikon|author= Mats Linder\n|accessdate= December 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThor Bj\u00f8rklund was born in [[Lillehammer]], [[Oppland]], Norway. He was apprenticed as a cabinet maker. He also attended the Arts and Crafts School in [[Oslo]]. He was employed for some time as a master [[carpenter]]. He began to experiment with a carpenter's [[Plane (tool)|plane]] in the hope that he could create something similar for use in the kitchen. He made cheese slicers in his workshop, and on 27 February 1925 he patented the model of cheese slicer which is today found in many households in [[Nordic countries]].<ref>[http://www.nortrade.com/sectors/news/the-cheese-slicer-a-norwegian-icon-celebrates-its-80th-birthday/ ''The Cheese Slicer \u2013 A Norwegian Icon celebrates its 80th birthday'' (Nortrade, Norway's official trade portal)]</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://inventors.about.com/od/famousinventions/fl/Who-Invented-the-Cheese-Slicer.htm|title = The History of the Cheese Slicer |publisher = inventors.about.com|accessdate= December 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1927, he started the firm known today as Thor Bj\u00f8rklund & S\u00f8nner AS. The company still produces cheese slicers in [[Lillehammer]], and has operated since November 17, 2009 as a subsidiary of Gudbrandsdal Industrier AS.<ref>[http://tasteful-inventions.blogspot.com/2010/02/thor-bjrklund-cheese-slicer.html ''Thor Bj\u00f8rklund: Cheese Slicer'' (Tasteful Inventions)]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.giax.no/bjorklund|title = Bj\u00f8rklund \n|publisher = Gudbrandsdal Industrier AS|accessdate= December 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bjorklund-1925.no/ Thor Bj\u00f8rklund & S\u00f8nner AS website]\n*[http://www.giax.no/ Gudbrandsdal Industrier AS website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bjorklund, Thor}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lillehammer]]\n[[Category:Norwegian company founders]]\n[[Category:Norwegian business executives]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian inventors]]\n[[Category:20th-century inventors]]\n\n\n{{Norway-engineer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[image:Osthyvel 20050723 001.jpg|thumb|250 px|''Osteh\u00f8vel'']]\n'''Thor Bj\u00f8rklund''' (October 30, 1889 \u2013 December 8, 1975) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[inventor]] and businessman. He is best known as the [[inventor]] of ''Osteh\u00f8vel'', a popular [[cheese slicer]] which developed into an important Norwegian export product.<ref>{{cite web|url=   https://nbl.snl.no/Thor_Bj%C3%B8rklund|title =    Thor Bj\u00f8rklund |publisher = Norsk biografisk leksikon|accessdate= December 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bjorklund-1925.no/index.php/en/about-us/51-history ''About Us: History'' (Thor Bj\u00f8rklund & S\u00f8nner AS)]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=   https://snl.no/osteh%C3%B8vel|title =    Osteh\u00f8vel |publisher =Store norske leksikon|author= Mats Linder\n|accessdate= December 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThor Bj\u00f8rklund was born in [[Lillehammer]], [[Oppland]], Norway. He was apprenticed as a cabinet maker. He also attended the Arts and Crafts School in [[Oslo]]. He was employed for some time as a master [[carpenter]]. He began to experiment with a carpenter\u2019s [[Plane (tool)|plane]] in the hope that he could create something similar for use in the kitchen. He made cheese slicers in his workshop, and on 27 February 1925 he patented the model of cheese slicer which is today found in many households in [[Nordic countries]].<ref>[http://www.nortrade.com/sectors/news/the-cheese-slicer-a-norwegian-icon-celebrates-its-80th-birthday/ ''The Cheese Slicer \u2013 A Norwegian Icon celebrates its 80th birthday'' (Nortrade,  Norway's official trade portal)]</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=   http://inventors.about.com/od/famousinventions/fl/Who-Invented-the-Cheese-Slicer.htm|title =    The History of the Cheese Slicer |publisher =     inventors.about.com|accessdate= December 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1927, he started the firm known today as Thor Bj\u00f8rklund & S\u00f8nner AS. The company still produces cheese slicers in [[Lillehammer]], and has operated since November 17, 2009 as a subsidiary of Gudbrandsdal Industrier AS.<ref>[http://tasteful-inventions.blogspot.com/2010/02/thor-bjrklund-cheese-slicer.html ''Thor Bj\u00f8rklund: Cheese Slicer'' (Tasteful Inventions)]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=   http://www.giax.no/bjorklund|title =     Bj\u00f8rklund \n|publisher =  Gudbrandsdal Industrier AS|accessdate= December 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bjorklund-1925.no/ Thor Bj\u00f8rklund & S\u00f8nner AS website]\n*[http://www.giax.no/ Gudbrandsdal Industrier AS website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bjorklund, Thor}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lillehammer]]\n[[Category:Norwegian company founders]]\n[[Category:Norwegian business executives]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian inventors]]\n[[Category:20th-century inventors]]\n\n\n{{Norway-engineer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "ur